ous, loaded silences, Laura Ishiguro traces how Britons used the post to navigate the family separations integral to their migration and to understand British Columbia as an uncontested settler home. This book argues that these letters and their writers played a critical role in laying the foundations of a powerful, personal settler colonial order that continues to structure the province today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishzBritish ColumbiavCorrespondence. 0aColonistszBritish ColumbiavCorrespondence. 0aFamilieszBritish ColumbiavSources. 0aImmigrantszBritish ColumbiavCorrespondence. 0aLetter writingzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLetter writingzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311141772140uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483845040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774838450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774838450/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-141772-1  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles